Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: Existing work on event schema induction has made significant progress by leveraging language models, path-based reasoning, and graph autoencoders—primarily in text-only or fully supervised settings. However, these approaches largely overlook the multimodal nature of real-world events, where visual and textual data co-occur but rarely come with aligned annotations (e.g., captions paired precisely with event mentions). While cross-modal learning is powerful, most methods assume strong supervision for alignment, which is expensive and impractical at scale. My idea builds on the insight that *events* are inherently grounded in both perception (vision) and narrative (language), and their semantic structure—such as argument roles (who did what to whom, when, where)—can be jointly inferred through weak correspondence signals between modalities. Unlike prior works that either focus solely on text (Paper 1 & 3) or rely on hand-crafted paths (Paper 2), I propose a novel framework that induces latent event schemas by aligning unpaired text narratives and video streams via shared event prototypes, without requiring explicit cross-modal labels. The key innovation lies in using **modality-invariant event prototypes** as anchors to guide the discovery of structured event graphs from noisy, asynchronous inputs. This approach enables weakly supervised schema induction where neither event boundaries nor correspondences are labeled. It differs fundamentally from previous methods by integrating multimodal grounding into schema learning, while maintaining scalability through self-supervised contrastive alignment and iterative refinement of hierarchical event structures. By doing so, it opens up new possibilities for zero-shot schema generalization across domains where only one modality may be available during inference.

